w plan is revealed after } 10...Be7 11.Bg2 O-O 12.Ng1 $1 Rfd8 ( { Black had put all his efforts into depriving the knight of the f4-square by } 12...Rad8 13.Nge2 g5 14.h4 h6 { in F. Olsen - M. Andersen, Avedore, 2023, when White could switch to a light-squared strategy with } 15.hxg5 hxg5 16.g4 $1 Qg6 17.Ng3 Bf6 18.Qe2 Rfe8 19.Kf1 $16 ) 13.Nge2 Bd6 { is an interesting idea to control the key f4-square, which strongly resembles the leading text with the only difference in the location of Ng1. Here it is on e2, while in the main line it will find itself on d2. } ( 13...Rd7 14.Nf4 Rad8 15.b3 Na5 16.bxc4 Nxc4 17.O-O g5 18.Nxe6 fxe6 ( { if } 18...Qxe6 { , then } 19.Qh5 { is a reminder that, besides the vulnerable d5-pawn, Black may soon experience problems with his king } ) 19.a4 $16 ) 14.O-O ( { the described small detail may be the reason why after } 14.Nxd5 Bxd5 15.Bxd5 Bxa3 16.Bxf7+ Qxf7 17.Rxa3 a5 { Black can rely on sufficient counterplay, for example } 18.O-O b5 19.Nf4 a4 $44 ) 14...Ne7 15.Re1 $14 ) ( { The insertion of } 10...Qd8 11.Bg2 { before } 11...Be7 { is seriously challenged by the stunning } 12.h4 $1 h6 ( 12...O-O $143 $6 13.Ng5 $1 $16 ) 13.Nd2 $14 O-O $140 14.Qh5 $36 { and the d5-pawn is in danger } ) ( 10...g6 11.Bg2 ( 11.h4 Bh6 12.h5 g5 $13 ) 11...Bh6 ( 11...Bg7 $6 { is pointless, White can complete his plan by } 12.Ng1 $1 ) 12.b3 O-O 13.bxc4 dxc4 14.Nd2 ( 14.O-O Rac8 ) ( 14.Rb1 Rab8 ) 14...Qe7 15.O-O $14 ) 11.Bg2 O-O 12.Nd2 { It is sensible to question immediately the central pair of pawns rather than } ( 12.h4 h6 13.O-O Rfd8 ) ( { or } 12.O-O Rfd8 { , when Black has higher chances to reinforce them. } ) 12...Rfd8 $1 ( { The retreat } 12...Ne7 { is a signal for } 13.b3 $1 ( 13.Nde4 dxe4 14.Nxe4 Qg6 15.Nxd6 Bg4 16.f3 Bxf3 17.Qxf3 Qxd6 18.O-O b5 $11 ) ( 13.O-O Bc7 ) 13...cxb3 14.Qxb3 Rfd8 15.Nb5 $14 ) ( { In case of } 12...Rad8 13.O-O Bb8 { White may follow the same strategy by } 14.b3 cxb3 15.Nxb3 $14 ( { a preferable capture to } 15.Qxb3 Rd7 { , when 