example } 11...a6 12.f4 axb5 13.fxe5 dxe5 14.Qc2 $5 ( 14.Bxb5+ Bd7 15.Bd3 $16 { is also good enough } ) 14...c4 15.e4 Qd6 16.Bh6 $16 ) 11.a4 $5 ( 11.e4 f4 ) ( 11.f4 Bxc3 12.bxc3 Nf6 ) 11...Nh6 12.Rb1 O-O 13.Bd2 $14 ) 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 7.cxd5 Nxd5 { This position can occur via the Panov attack as well. } 8.Qb3 { The most principled continuation. } ( { Another popular option is } 8.Bc4 { , after which Black can either transpose to the leading text by 8...Nxc3 or play } 8...Nb6 9.Bb3 $140 Bg7 10.O-O O-O { with mutual chances. } ) 8...e6 { The more solid, but probably not the better one of the two reasonable replies. } ( 8...Nxc3 9.Bc4 $1 { Only this intermediate move preserves White's hopes for an advantage: } 9...Nd5 ( 9...e6 10.bxc3 { and Black has yet to find a safe path to equality: } 10...Bd7 { is a reversed move order, by which Black is preventing the immediate Bc1-a3 as well. } ( 10...Bg7 11.Ba3 Bf8 $6 ( { the textmove is sacrificing tempi with the only purpose to let the king leave the central zone. However, in his prime time, Botvinnik has already demonstrated how dangerous White's permanent initiative on the dark squares can be. Black should better try } 11...Na5 $6 { , which is actually preferable to the same jump (see the next subline) on the previous move, for example } 12.Bb5+ Bd7 13.Qb2 Qb6 14.Bxd7+ Kxd7 15.Qe2 $14 ) 12.Bxf8 Kxf8 13.h4 $1 h5 ( 13...Kg7 14.h5 $16 ) ( 13...h6 14.h5 g5 15.O-O Kg7 16.Qb2 $16 ) 14.Bd3 ( 14.Qb2 $5 ) 14...Kg7 15.O-O b6 16.Rae1 $16 ) ( { in case of } 10...Na5 11.Bb5+ Bd7 12.Qa4 $1 Nc6 { we can expect from White to force matters in the view of the "centralized" enemy king, so } 13.d5 $1 ( { much more restrained is } 13.O-O a6 14.Be2 $14 ) 13...exd5 14.O-O Be7 ( 14...f6 $6 15.Qb3 $16 ) 15.Bh6 { is a real acid test for the opponent. The latter's best bet is } 15...Qa5 { , but White's initiative is ongoing even without the queens, e.g. } 16.Rfe1 ( { alternatively, they can be preserved, for instance } 16.Qb3 $5 O-O-O 17.Rab1 ) 16.