e fact that f7-f6 is often a must, bring his king to the f7-square at least. The eventual problems in front of him are more strategic than tactical, for he will have to find a proper place for his Bc8 after } 11.Bxc6+ bxc6 12.O-O { , for example: } 12...Qd5 ( 12...Bg7 $6 { is dubious, for it is giving up any control over the c5-square and by this the opportunity to push his pawn there - } 13.Bf4 $1 ( { worth a try is even } 13.Qa3 Qe7 14.b3 Qxa3 15.Bxa3 f6 16.Rac1 Kd7 $140 17.Nd2 $14 ) 13...O-O 14.Rfc1 $16 ( 14.Qa3 $5 ) ) ( 12...Be7 13.Bd2 $5 ( { less flexible is } 13.Be3 Qd5 14.Rfc1 f6 15.Nd2 Kf7 $11 ) 13...Qd5 14.Qc2 f6 15.Rfe1 Kf7 ( { details about the insertion of } 15...a5 16.a3 { can be found in the line with 12...Qd5, see below } ) 16.b4 $1 { It is important for White to grasp the first moment, when c6-c5 is really playable, and respectively prevent it. } 16...g5 17.h3 Bd7 ( 17...h5 $2 18.Bxg5 $1 ) 18.Bc3 h5 19.Nd2 Be8 20.Nf1 Kg7 21.Qe2 $14 ) ( 12...f6 13.Re1 Qd5 { is quite similar, White can slightly deviate from the last note by } 14.Qe3 $5 Be7 15.Bd2 O-O ( 15...g5 16.Bc3 Kf7 17.Nd2 h5 18.Ne4 $14 ) 16.b4 $1 ( { as soon as Ke8 has left the central zone, White should seriously consider the queenside advances, for instance } 16.Bc3 c5 $1 17.Rad1 a5 $1 18.h4 Ra6 $11 ) 16...Bd6 17.a3 Re8 18.Bc3 $14 [%cal Gf3d2,Gd2e4] ) 13.Qc2 f6 14.Bd2 a5 $5 ( { as said, } 14...Kf7 { should be answered with } 15.b4 $1 ) 15.Rfe1 Kf7 16.Bc3 Bb7 17.Rad1 Be7 18.a3 c5 ( 18...Rhd8 19.Qe2 Ba6 20.Qe3 $14 ) 19.dxc5 Qxc5 { The trade of the problematic c-pawn is definitely an achievement for Black, but he has yet to cope with threats on the opposite wing - } 20.Qe2 Qc6 21.Rd4 Rhd8 22.Rh4 ( { alternatively, White can win the e6-pawn by means of the spectacular } 22.Rf4 Rd5 23.Qe5 $1 { , for instance } 23...Ke8 24.Qxe6 Qxe6 25.Rxe6 Rd1+ 26.Re1 Rxe1+ 27.Nxe1 Rc8 $44 ) 22...Kg8 ( 22...h5 23.Qe3 $40 ) 23.Qxe6+ ( 23.Rc4 Qa6 ) 23...Qxe6 24.Rxe6 Rd1+ 25.Re1 Rxe1+ 26.Nxe1 a4 27.Nc2 $14 ) 9.Bb5 Bg7 10.O-O O-O 11.Bxc6 $1 { The same strategical idea of saddling the opponent with a passive Bc8. Indeed, Black has already succeeded to castle, but the additional presence of a pair of knights in comparison to 8...Nxc3 9.Bc4 Nd5 must be a concern for him, as the c5-square may be quickly occupied by the best blockading piece. } 11...bxc6 12.Re1 $1 { The move order matters, White is making this sound positional move before deciding about the route of Nc3. } ( 12.Na4 { seems premature in the view of } 12...Qd6 ) 12...Qc7 { It is far from easy to point out a better alternative: } ( 12...Qd6 $6 { is just exposing the queen to the enemy minor pieces - } 13.Ne4 Qb4 ( 13...Qc7 14.Bd2 Rb8 15.Qa3 f6 16.Rac1 $16 { Vidit - Nepomniachtchi, Kolkata, 2019 } ) 14.Qc2 a5 15.a3 ( 15.Bd2 $16 ) 15...Qb6 16.Nc5 Re8 17.Ne5 f6 18.Nc4 Qc7 19.Bd2 $16 { and Black lasted for only 13 more moves in Giri - Mamedyarov, Wijk aan Zee, 2018 } ) ( 12...Nxc3 $6 { does not solve the opening tasks for a familiar reason - after } 13.bxc3 { the a3-f8 diagonal will entirely belong to Bc1, e.g. } 13...Ba6 ( 13...c5 $2 14.Ba3 ) 14.Ba3 Re8 15.Ne5 Qd5 16.Bc5 $16 { Donchenko - Gledura, Budapest, 2018 } ) ( 12...Qb6 13.Qc2 $1 { leaves Black in trouble of how to stop Nc3-a4: } 13...Nb4 ( 13...Nxc3 14.bxc3 Qa5 ( { preventing } 14...Rd8 $6 15.Ba3 { , which saw Grandelius - Abasov, chess24.com INT, 2020, when } 15...Ba6 16.Bc5 Qc7 17.c4 $16 { is quite similar to the strategically difficult position in the abovementioned game Donchenko - Gledura } ) 15.Bf4 Ba6 16.Bd6 Rfd8 17.Bc5 $14 ) ( 13...Rb8 14.Na4 Qb5 15.Qd1 e5 16.Nxe5 Bf5 17.Nc3 $14 ) ( 13...a5 14.Ne4 ( 14.Na4 ) 14...e5 15.dxe5 Bg4 16.Nd6 Bxf3 17.gxf3 Qc7 18.Qe4 $14 ) 14.Qd1 Rd8 ( { the attempt at displaying activity by } 14...Ba6 $6 15.Na4 Qb5 16.Nc5 Rfd8 17.a3 Nd3 { will cost the poor light-squared bishop after } 18.a4 $1 Qc4 19.b3 Qc3 20.Bd2 Bxd4 $140 21.Nxa6 Qxa1 22.Qxa1 Bxa1 23.Rxa1 $16 ) ( 14...c5 15.Na4 Qb5 16.Nxc5 Bb7 17.Ne5 Rfd8 18.Bf4 $14 ) 15.Bg5 $1 f6