 { [%evp 0,35,33,21,48,12,12,20,23,36,10,23,23,-1,-8,7,11,5,9,11,39,28,37,36,63, 57,32,28,25,22,52,44,49,40,55,25,27,31] } 1.Nf3 c5 2.c4 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 { A more direct way to stop d2-d4 than 3...g6, which is also urging White to fight for that key central square by } 4.e3 Nf6 ( 4...f5 { is tempting, though a bit optimistic. } { Critical is } 5.d4 $1 ( 5.Be2 $5 ) 5...e4 { and now: } 6.Ng1 $5 { deserves serious attention - } ( { The main theoretical line is } 6.d5 exf3 7.dxc6 dxc6 8.Qxd8+ Kxd8 9.gxf3 Nf6 10.b3 Bd6 11.Bb2 Ke7 12.O-O-O ( 12.h4 Be6 ) 12...Be6 $14 { Giri - So, Saint Louis, 2015 } ) 6...d6 ( 6...Nf6 7.Nge2 { and perhaps Black's best is to transpose to the text by 7...d6 rather than } 7...cxd4 8.Nxd4 $14 ) 7.Nge2 Nf6 8.h4 { and now: } 8...Be7 ( 8...g6 9.Bd2 $5 ( 9.Nf4 Bh6 ) 9...Bg7 ( 9...Bh6 10.Nd5 $1 ) 10.dxc5 dxc5 11.Nf4 O-O 12.Qb3 Ne5 13.Be2 Bd7 14.O-O-O Qb6 ( 14...Qe8 { is aimed against any jump to the d5-square, White can either check the consequences of the capture of the b7-pawn or keep it in reserve by } 15.h5 g5 16.h6 Bh8 { , when he has a pleasant choice between } 17.Nh5 ( { and } 17.Nh3 ) ) 15.h5 Qxb3 16.axb3 $14 ) 9.Nf4 O-O 10.Be2 $14 ) 5.d4 { A consistent continuation. } ( { The textmove can be preceded by } 5.Be2 ) 5...e4 ( { A major alternative is to insert } 5...cxd4 6.exd4 { before } 6...e4 { - } 7.Ne5 { and now: } 7...Bb4 { is Black's main preference, planning to harass both knights - } ( 7...d6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.d5 c5 10.Be2 Be7 11.Bf4 $14 ) ( 7...Qa5 $2 8.c5 $18 ) ( 7...Be7 8.Be2 O-O 9.O-O $14 ) ( 7...Bd6 { is logically questioning the centralized knight, to which White can go for the e4-pawn with the help of the witty sequence } 8.Ng4 $1 ( 8.c5 Bb8 9.Nc4 d5 10.cxd6 O-O $13 ) 8...Nxg4 9.Qxg4 O-O 10.Bh6 $1 Qf6 11.Be3 Bb4 12.Qxe4 d5 $1 { A consequent new pawn sacrifice - Black has to prove compensation as soon as possible. After } 13.cxd5 ( 13.Qxd5 Rd8 14.Qg5 Qxg5 15.Bxg5 Rxd4 16.a3 Bxc3+ 17.bxc3 Re4+ 18.Be3 Na5 $44 ) 13...Bf5 14.Qf4 Ne7 15.g4 { he must already invest a piece: } 15...Nxd5 ( 15...Qb6 16.gxf5 Nxd5 17.Qg4 $1 Nxc3 18.Rg1 $1 Nd5+ 19.Kd1 Qf6 20.Bc4 ( 20.Bg5 Qb6 ) 20...Nxe3+ 21.fxe3 Rfe8 22.Ke2 Rac8 23.Bb3 $14 ) 16.Qxf5 Qc6 17.O-O-O $1 Bxc3 ( 17...Nxe3 $6 18.fxe3 Qxh1 19.Bd3 Qxh2 { allows } 20.Nd5 $16 { , which has to explain why this knight should better be eliminated in advance } ) 18.bxc3 Rac8 19.c4 { and here } 19...Nxe3 20.fxe3 Qxh1 { leads to an interesting endgame, which is slightly better for White with his two pawns for the exchange after } 21.Qxh7+ Kxh7 22.Bd3+ g6 23.Rxh1 $14 ) 8.Be2 { and now: } 8...Qa5 { is the logical follow-up, the pin of added to the attack at Ne5: } ( 8...Qe7 9.Bf4 $36 ) ( 8...O-O 9.O-O Ne7 ( 9...Re8 10.Bf4 $16 ) 10.f3 d6 11.Ng4 $14 ) 9.Nxc6 { is less adventurous, White seems to have a little pull: } ( 9.O-O $5 { is an intriguing pawn sacrifice - } 9...Nxe5 10.dxe5 Qxe5 11.Bd2 Be7 { (a necessary precaution against 12.Nxe4) } 12.Be3 ( { to } 12.Re1 d5 $1 { is well-timed, e.g. } 13.cxd5 O-O 14.Bf3 Bf5 $11 ) 12...O-O 13.Bd4 Qg5 14.Re1 { and here } 14...d5 { is once again Black's best shot at simplifying with equality - } 15.cxd5 Bb4 $11 ) 9...Bxc3+ ( 9...bxc6 10.Bd2 O-O 11.Rc1 d5 12.O-O $14 ) ( 9...dxc6 10.O-O O-O 11.Bd2 Re8 ( 11...Be6 12.a3 Bxc3 13.bxc3 b6 14.Re1 Qf5 15.h3 Qg6 16.Kh2 Nd7 17.Bf4 $14 ) 12.a3 Bxc3 13.bxc3 $1 ( 13.Bxc3 Qg5 ) 13...Bf5 14.h3 e3 $5 15.Bxe3 ( 15.fxe3 $6 Bg6 $44 ) 15...Qxc3 16.Qc1 $14 ) 10.bxc3 bxc6 ( 10...dxc6 $6 11.Bd2 { is similar to the variation from above, but White has economized time on a2-a3 } ) 11.Qb3 $5 ( { White can show his intentions on the queenside after } 11.O-O O-O { as well } ) 11...O-O 12.Qa3 Qf5 13.O-O ( 13.Qd6 Ba6 ) 13...d5 14.Rb1 Qg6 15.Re1 Bf5 ( 15...Bh3 $6 16.Bf1 ) 16.Rb2 $14 ) 6.d5 $1 ( { Another line goes on with } 6.Ne5 g6 ) 6...exf3 7.dxc6 dxc6 { The most original of the three possible captures: } ( 7...fxg2 8.cxd7+ { looks easier for White to play due to the pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal, for example } 8...B