 { [%evp 0,27,26,15,46,20,16,6,29,4,22,22,21,9,16,21,37,38,39,35,20,28,62,80,68, 79,61,17,52,59] } 1.Nf3 c5 2.c4 Nc6 3.Nc3 e6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 Bb4 ( { In reply to } 5...a6 $6 { White can try to prove that this little pawn move is a waste of time by continuing in the spirit of Chapter 7 with } 6.Nxc6 $1 ( { besides, White can opt for } 6.e4 { at once, with a nice version of the Maroczy bind } ) 6...bxc6 ( 6...dxc6 $6 7.Qxd8+ Kxd8 8.Bf4 $16 ) 7.e4 Qc7 8.Bd3 Nf6 9.O-O Be7 10.Be3 d6 11.f4 O-O 12.Kh1 Bb7 13.Qf3 $16 ) ( { Unlike the similar thrust in Chapter 9 (where it comfortably equalizes with Nf6 instead of Nc6 on the board) here } 5...d5 { is simply providing White with numerous good options to choose from - } 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bf4 ( 7.e4 $5 dxe4 8.Bb5 ) 7...a6 8.g3 ( 8.e4 $5 ) 8...Nf6 ( 8...Bc5 9.Be3 $1 ) 9.Bg2 Bc5 10.Nxc6 bxc6 11.O-O O-O 12.Rc1 $14 ) ( 5...Bc5 6.Nb3 { looks simpler, for the game can continue analogously to the leading text after } ( { not so clear is } 6.Ndb5 Nf6 7.Bf4 ( 7.Nd6+ $143 Ke7 ) 7...O-O 8.Bc7 Qe7 9.Bd6 Bxd6 10.Qxd6 Qd8 $5 ( { it is the same idea (planning to chase the opponent's pieces) in a relevant Sicilian line, which has brought back this variation on the map rather than the old continuation } 10...Ne8 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O $14 ) 11.e4 Qa5 12.O-O-O a6 13.Na3 Rd8 $14 [%cal Gf6e8] ) 6...Bb4 ( { Black can hardly be satisfied by } 6...Be7 7.e4 ) 7.g3 { and now: } 7...Nf6 ( 7...d5 8.cxd5 exd5 ( 8...Qxd5 9.Qxd5 exd5 10.Bd2 $14 ) 9.Bg2 ) 8.Bg2 { is quite similar to the leading text, the knight's new location does not influence the general verdict of the position as preferable for White. } 8...d5 9.cxd5 exd5 { is an attempt to clarify the structure in the center, White stays on top after } 10.O-O Bxc3 ( 10...Be6 11.Nd4 $14 ) 11.bxc3 O-O 12.Bg5 h6 13.Bxf6 Qxf6 14.Qxd5 Qxc3 15.Qb5 $14 ) 6.g3 $1 { Well played - now White is about to get a nice version of the Nimzo with 4. Nf3 c5 5.g3, in which all the counterattacking options with Nf6-e4 are excluded. } ( 6.Ndb5 Nf6 7.Bf4 O-O 8.Bc7 Qe7 9.Bd6 { - 5...Bc5 6.Ndb5. } ) 6...Nf6 ( 6...Qa5 { must be Black's last opportunity to deviate, though } 7.Ndb5 $1 [%cal Ga2a3] { is hard to meet. } ) 7.Bg2 O-O 8.O-O Qe7 $5 { A concrete idea, by which Black keeps all the options for his d-pawn. } ( { Risky is } 8...Bxc3 9.bxc3 { and even though } 9...Qa5 { stops 10.Ba3 for the moment, the concerns about the weakened complex of dark squares remain, e.g. } 10.Qc2 $14 ) ( 8...a6 9.Nc2 $16 ) ( 8...d5 9.cxd5 exd5 10.Bg5 Be6 { is almost the same as a line from above, but with Nd4 still placed in the center White is practically a tempo up - } 11.Rc1 h6 12.Be3 $14 ) 9.Na4 $1 { An adequate reaction - Black has to take care about his Bb4. } ( { His last move will be justified after } 9.Nc2 Bxc3 10.bxc3 Rd8 { , meeting } 11.Ba3 { with } 11...d6 $11 ) 9...d5 ( { More passive is } 9...Rd8 10.a3 Bd6 11.b4 ( 11.Be3 $5 Be5 12.Qd2 ) 11...Be5 12.Bb2 Nxd4 13.Bxd4 Bxd4 14.Qxd4 d6 15.Rfd1 $14 { Khismatullin - Zvjaginsev, Dagomys, 2010. } ) 10.cxd5 Nxd4 { Relatively the best option, compared to: } ( 10...Nxd5 $6 11.Nxc6 bxc6 12.Qc2 $16 ) ( 10...exd5 11.Be3 $14 ) 11.Qxd4 Nxd5 12.a3 Bd6 13.Bd2 { with typical for the Catalan pressure - } 13...Bd7 14.Nc3 $14 

