d, even more, there is a crafty trap like } 8.Bd3 Ne5 9.O-O Qd6 $1 $11 ) 7...d5 $1 ( { In case of } 7...Be7 { White should not any longer hesitate about } 8.e4 $1 O-O $140 9.Be2 Qc7 10.O-O b6 11.f4 d6 12.Be3 Bb7 13.Rc1 $14 { Giri - Svidler, Stavanger, 2014. } ) 8.Be3 $1 { This developing and attacking move cannot be prevented anyway. } ( { Clearly premature is } 8.cxd5 Nxd5 $11 { , see the next annotation. } ) 8...Qc7 $5 ( 8...d4 { could have worked after a double exchange on d5 in the abovementioned line with 8.cxd5 Nxd5, while here White is able to pick up some material, as witnessed by } 9.Nxd4 Ng4 10.Na4 $1 Nxe3 11.Nxb6 Nxd1 12.Nxa8 Nxb2 13.Nc7+ Kd7 14.Ncb5 e5 15.Nc2 a6 16.Nc3 Nxc4 17.e3 $16 { with every chance to convert the extra exchange } ) ( 8...Qd8 { levels the tempi if Nb3 returns to the center - } 9.cxd5 Nxd5 ( 9...exd5 10.g3 Be7 11.Bg2 Be6 12.O-O O-O 13.Nd4 $14 { is transposing to the standard Tarrasch } ) 10.Nxd5 exd5 11.g3 { A logical set-up, as in the main line. } 11...a5 ( { or } 11...Be7 12.Bg2 Bf6 { , when White can either defend his b-pawn or enter } 13.O-O O-O 14.Qxd5 Qxd5 15.Bxd5 Re8 16.Rfd1 Bxb2 17.Ra2 Bf6 18.Nc5 $14 ) 12.Bg2 a4 13.Nd4 Qa5+ 14.Bd2 Qb6 { A reminder of the same motif on move 5, here White must reinforce his Nd4 by } 15.Bc3 Bc5 16.e3 { with easier play after } 16...O-O 17.O-O Rd8 18.Re1 Nxd4 19.exd4 Bf8 20.h4 Be6 21.Qd2 $14 ) 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.Nxd5 exd5 11.g3 ( { A sound alternative is } 11.Rc1 Be7 { , when White can even look for a perfect from a strategical point of view exchange of the dark-squared bishops. } ) 11...Be7 12.Bg2 O-O 13.O-O Bf6 14.Qd2 $1 ( { Less precise is the direct } 14.Nd4 { Wojtaszek - Tregubov, Tallinn, 2016, in the view of } 14...Bg4 $11 ) 14...Rd8 15.Nd4 $14 

