d4 16.Bd3 Bf5 17.Bxf5 Rfe8 18.Be4 f5 19.O-O Rxe4 20.Qh3 Rd8 $11 ) 9...Bxb4 10.f3 d5 11.a3 $1 { The first subtlety, by which White forces the exchange of Bb4. } 11...Bxc3 12.Qxc3 d4 13.c5 $1 { This new intermezzo leads by force to an endgame on two results due to the pair of bishops - } 13...dxc3 ( 13...Qd8 14.Qc2 $14 ) 14.cxb6 cxb2 15.Bxb2 axb6 16.Bd4 O-O 17.Bxb6 Bd7 18.Be2 Rfc8 19.Kd2 $14 ) 9.f3 $1 Nf2 10.Na4 Qc7 11.Nxc5 Nxh1 { and the fight in this highly unbalanced position is reaching its climax: } 12.f4 $5 $146 ( 12.g3 { looks like the easiest way to trap the nasty knight, but there are many intricacies along it - } 12...O-O ( 12...Ne5 $5 13.Qe3 $140 O-O ) 13.Bg2 ( 13.Na4 f5 $132 ) 13...Na5 $1 ( 13...Nxg3 $6 14.hxg3 Qxg3+ ( 14...Ne5 15.f4 $1 Qxc5 16.fxe5 Qg1+ 17.Bf1 Qxg3+ 18.Qf2 Qxe5 19.Be3 $36 ) 15.Qf2 Qc7 { So far F. Svane - D. Lazavik, Chess.com INT, 2022, in which White could claim an advantage with } 16.f4 $16 ) 14.Nd3 Nxg3 { is the correct move order, the hanging c4-pawn apparently comes in handy for Black, e.g. } 15.Nf4 ( 15.hxg3 Nxc4 16.Qf2 d5 $132 ) 15...Nxc4 16.Qc3 g5 $1 17.hxg3 gxf4 18.Bf1 ( 18.Bxf4 e5 ) 18...d5 19.Bxc4 Qxc4 20.Qf6 Qc5 21.Qg5+ $11 ) 12...O-O 13.Be2 { has the idea to win Nh1 by the king, though this will take time. } 13...d5 ( { Black should urgently open the position, half-measures like } 13...d6 $6 14.Na4 { will hardly suffice } ) 14.Kf1 ( { it is possible to insert } 14.cxd5 exd5 { before } 15.Kf1 { , but Black is able to initiate counterplay by means of } 15...dxe4 16.Kg1 Ne7 $1 17.Nb3 Rd8 18.Qc3 Qxc3 19.bxc3 Nd5 20.c4 $140 Nc3 21.Bf1 Rd1 22.Ne3 Re1 23.Kxh1 Ne2 24.Bb2 Rxa1 25.Bxa1 Nxf4 { with approximately balanced endgame } ) 14...dxc4 ( { Black can also precede the textmove - } 14...Qe7 $5 15.Na4 dxc4 16.Bxc4 Rd8 17.Qe1 Rb8 18.Bb5 Bd7 19.Nc3 { , when } 19...Nb4 $1 20.Nxb4 $140 Bxb5+ 21.Nxb5 Qc5 $1 { is the key to counterplay, the game can continue with } 22.Nc3 Qxb4 23.Qe2 b5 24.Be3 a5 25.Kg1 { and here Black can throw yet another surprise at the opponent by } 25...Qc4 $1 { with a very entertaining balanced ending after } 26.Qxc4 bxc4 27.Bc1 a4 28.a3 Rb3 29.g4 Rxc3 30.bxc3 Rd1+ 31.Kg2 h6 $11 ) 15.e5 b6 16.Ne4 Bb7 17.Qd6 Qd8 $1 18.Qxd8 Raxd8 { An irrational situation - similar to one of the lines from above, the sample ones below prove that it is not at all easy for White to get rid of the errant knight: } 19.Nd6 ( 19.Nc3 f6 20.exf6 Rxf6 21.Kg1 e5 22.fxe5 ( 22.f5 Nd4 23.Bxc4+ Kh8 24.Ne3 b5 $13 ) 22...Nxe5 23.Bg5 Rg6 24.Bxd8 Rxg2+ 25.Kf1 Rxh2 26.Bc7 { and all of a sudden the piece, which seemed doomed a dozen of moves ago, is going to deliver an amusing perpetual after } 26...Ng3+ 27.Ke1 Nf3+ 28.Bxf3 Bxf3 29.Rc1 Rh1+ 30.Kd2 Nf1+ 31.Ke1 Ng3+ $11 ) 19...Ba8 20.Be3 c3 ( 20...f6 $143 21.Bxc4 g6 22.Bxe6+ Kg7 23.Kg1 fxe5 24.fxe5 Nxe5 25.Rd1 $14 ) 21.bxc3 f6 22.Bc4 g5 23.Bxe6+ Kg7 24.fxg5 ( 24.Nf5+ Kg6 ) 24...fxe5+ 25.Nf5+ Kg6 26.Ke2 Rfe8 27.Nh4+ Kh5 28.Nf5 ( 28.Bf7+ Kxh4 29.Bxe8 Rxe8 30.Rxh1 Ne7 $11 ) 28...Kg6 $11 ) ( 6...Be7 $6 { is imprecise on the account of } 7.Bf4 $1 { with the idea to meet } 7...d6 { with } 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.e5 dxe5 10.Qxd8+ Bxd8 11.Bxe5 $14 [%cal Ge1c1] { , when the better structure and the queenside majority assure White of a pleasant and lasting advantage. In particular, his second bishop will appear on the big diagonal and exert pressure along it. } ) ( 6...a6 $6 { seems even worse in the view of the analogous } 7.Nxc6 $1 dxc6 ( 7...bxc6 8.e5 Ng8 9.Bf4 $16 ) 8.Qxd8+ Kxd8 9.e5 ( 9.Bf4 $5 ) 9...Nd7 10.Bf4 $1 Kc7 11.O-O-O b5 12.Ne4 $16 ) ( 6...d5 $2 { runs into } 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Bb5 $1 Bd7 $140 9.exd5 Nxd4 10.Bxd7+ Qxd7 11.Qxd4 $16 ) ( { We have already got enough evidence about the importance of the e5-square, so } 6...Qc7 { is sensible. White's most natural answer is } 7.Be2 ( 7.Be3 $5 Bb4 8.f3 d5 $140 9.Qb3 ) { and now } 7...Nxd4 ( { pointless is } 7...Bb4 $6 8.Ndb5 { and, in comparison to 7.Be3, here in reply to 8...Qa5 White can simply castle, so it is over with the pin - } 