al Ge3d4,Ga1c1] ) ( 8...O-O $2 { is strongly met by } 9.e5 $1 Qa5 10.Bf4 $1 Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 Qxc3+ 12.Kf1 Ne8 13.h4 $1 $16 { with a huge play on the kingside for the sacrificed pawn. } ) 9.O-O O-O 10.h3 $5 ( { Another possible move is } 10.Qe2 ) 10...Bc5 ( 10...Bxc3 { is the most consequent way to proceed, if Black wishes to play on in the spirit of the Nimzo - } 11.bxc3 d6 ( 11...Qe7 12.f4 d6 { - 11...d6 } ) 12.f4 ( { White can rely on compensation after } 12.c5 $5 dxc5 13.Qc2 { , but the textmove is consistent at least } ) 12...Qe7 ( 12...exf4 $2 13.Bxf4 Re8 14.Qf3 Be6 { Oparin - Gelfand, Warsaw, 2021, } 15.Rae1 $16 ) 13.Qf3 exf4 14.Bxf4 Nd7 15.Qg3 Ne5 16.c5 Nxd3 17.Qxd3 dxc5 18.Rae1 Be6 $2 ( { now Black is depriving himself of a rook lift to the 6th rank, which is possible in the end of the sample line } 18...Rd8 19.Qg3 Qf8 20.Bg5 Ba6 21.Rf3 $44 ) 19.Qg3 Rfe8 ( { in case of } 19...Rad8 { White can hinder the mentioned idea by means of } 20.e5 $1 { , after which his attack exclusively on the dark squares is practically unstoppable, for instance } 20...Qc7 21.Re3 Kh8 22.Bg5 Rd5 23.Qf4 $40 [%cal Gg5f6] ) 20.Bd6 Qd7 21.Be5 f6 22.Rd1 Qb7 23.Rxf6 $16 { F. Svane - J. Bjerre, chess24.com INT, 2022 } ) ( 10...d6 { keeps many options open, White can challenge this restrained move with } 11.Na4 $5 ( 11.Be3 { allows } 11...Bxc3 12.bxc3 Be6 [%cal Gd6d5] ) 11...d5 $1 ( { Black must take care of his Bb4 and react adequately rather than } 11...h6 12.a3 Ba5 13.b4 Bc7 14.Be3 $14 [%cal Ga1c1,Gd1e2,Gf1d1] { Oparin - Fier, Chess.com INT, 2020 } ) 12.a3 { , when there is a choice: } 12...Bd6 { is much more active and can inspire lively complications after } ( 12...Be7 13.exd5 cxd5 14.cxd5 Bb7 ( { White can rely in the long run on his small queenside majority after } 14...Nxd5 15.Re1 $14 ) ( { and } 14...Qxd5 15.Nc3 Qe6 16.Be3 $14 { as well } ) 15.Re1 Qxd5 16.Bf1 Qxd1 17.Rxd1 Bc6 18.Nc3 $14 ) 13.cxd5 cxd5 14.exd5 e4 15.Bc2 Ng4 $1 16.f4 ( 16.hxg4 $2 Qh4 $40 ) ( 16.Bxe4 Qh4 17.Nc3 f5 18.Bf3 Rb8 $44 ) ( 16.g3 { results in a beautiful perpetual after the stunning } 16...Nh2 $1 17.Kxh2 Qh4 18.Kg1 Bxg3 19.Qe2 Bh2+ $1 20.Kxh2 Qxh3+ 21.Kg1 Ba6 $1 22.Qxa6 Qg4+ $11 ) 16...exf3 17.Qxf3 ( 17.Rxf3 Re8 18.Bf4 Bxf4 19.Rxf4 Ne3 20.Qd2 Nxc2 21.Qxc2 Qxd5 $11 ) 17...Nh2 $1 18.Qd3 g6 19.Rf2 Qh4 20.Be3 Ng4 $1 ( { the position is more and more resembling the fabulous Marshall attack and the unforgettable clash between Capablanca and the author. If Black is unwilling to sacrifice the knight again, then he can play } 20...Re8 { before opting for the jump in the text } ) 21.hxg4 Qh2+ 22.Kf1 a5 23.Ke1 Ba6 24.Qd4 Be5 25.Qd1 Rad8 26.Bb3 ( 26.Nc5 Bg3 27.Nxa6 Qxg2 28.Ke2 Bxf2 29.Qh1 Qxh1 30.Rxh1 Bxe3 31.Kxe3 Rxd5 $11 ) 26...Rb8 $1 27.Nc5 ( { one can hardly expect a repetition like } 27.Bc2 Rbd8 $11 { in such crazy situation } ) 27...Rfe8 28.Kd2 ( 28.Nxa6 $6 Bf4 $1 { can end disastrously } ) 28...Bg3 $1 29.Qf3 Bxf2 30.Qxf2 Qe5 31.Bd4 ( { now repeating moves is the most reasonable decision, for Black is at least equal after } 31.Rb1 Rxb3 $1 32.Nxb3 Qe4 33.Re1 Qd3+ 34.Kc1 Qxb3 ) 31...Qg5+ 32.Be3 Qe5 $11 ) ( 10...h6 11.Be3 { and only now } 11...d5 12.cxd5 $140 Bxc3 13.bxc3 cxd5 14.exd5 Nxd5 { does not reach full equality after } 15.Re1 Qf6 16.c4 Nxe3 17.Rxe3 Be6 18.Rc1 $14 [%cal Gd1a4] ) 11.Re1 d6 ( 11...Bd4 { is a serious try to justify Black's previous move, based on } 12.Be3 ( 12.Ne2 Bc5 { is a kind of silent draw repetition } ) 12...c5 { , thus occupying the vulnerable d4-square. After } 13.Bxd4 cxd4 14.Nd5 d6 { G. Oparin - T. Nguyen, Tornelo INT, 2021, } 15.f4 $14 { is critical } ) ( 11...Re8 $6 12.Be3 Bxe3 13.Rxe3 Rb8 14.Qd2 d6 15.Rd1 $16 { and Black will face continuous pressure on his d6-pawn, Oparin - Cheparinov, Tornelo INT, 2021. } ) 12.Be3 Bd4 ( { Black has found himself in a similarly grim situation after } 12...Bxe3 $6 13.Rxe3 Be6 14.Be2 Qc7 15.Qd2 Rfd8 16.Rd1 Rd7 17.Rg3 Qd8 18.b3 $14 { in Artemiev - Parligras, Chess.com INT, 2020. } ) 13.Bxd4 exd4 14.Na4 Nd7 ( 14...c5