 ( { this small provocation is an attempt at refining } 13.dxc5 bxc5 14.Rac1 Qb6 15.Rfd1 Rfd8 $11 { with a dynamically balanced position in Karjakin - Kramnik, Moscow, 2018 } ) 13...h6 ( 13...cxd4 14.Nxd4 Nxd4 15.Qxd4 Bf6 16.Qd2 $14 ) ( 13...Bf6 14.Qd2 { and, having lured the dark-squared bishop, White is preparing to press on the c5-pawn, see the text as well } ) 14.Rac1 Bf6 15.Qd2 cxd4 16.Nxd4 Nxd4 17.Bxd4 $14 ) 9.a3 ( 9.h4 Ndb4 10.Qb1 f5 $13 ) 9...b6 { is leaving Nc6 hanging for a while and White can show resourcefulness by unleashing } ( 9...Bf6 10.Bd3 h6 11.h4 $36 ) ( 9...f5 { should better be played in reply to h2-h4, e.g. } 10.Rd1 Bd7 11.Be2 $14 ) ( 9...Nxc3 10.Bxc3 b6 ( 10...Qd6 11.Bc4 $14 ) 11.h4 h6 ( 11...Bf6 12.Ng5 g6 13.f4 $40 ) 12.Bc4 $36 ( { stronger than } 12.g4 Bb7 13.Rh3 Rc8 $13 { , as in Keymer - Martirosyan, Chess.com INT, 2021 } ) 12...Bf6 13.Ng5 $1 Bxg5 14.hxg5 Qxg5 15.O-O-O $40 ) ( 9...Bd7 10.Be2 ( { as said, Black is ready for both } 10.Bd3 h6 ) ( { and } 10.h4 f5 { with mutual chances } ) 10...Rc8 11.O-O Bf6 12.Ne4 $5 ( { instead, the practice has seen } 12.Nxd5 Bxb2 13.Qxb2 exd5 14.Qc3 b6 15.d4 Qf6 16.Rac1 cxd4 17.Nxd4 Nxd4 18.Qxd4 Qxd4 19.exd4 Rxc1 20.Rxc1 Rc8 21.Rxc8+ Bxc8 $11 { and the rest of the game could be spared, Keymer - Mamedyarov, Berlin, 2022 } ) 12...Bxb2 ( 12...Be7 13.Rfd1 f5 14.Nc3 $14 ) 13.Qxb2 Qe7 14.Rac1 b6 15.Rfd1 $14 ) 10.h4 $1 f5 11.d4 cxd4 12.Nxd5 Qxd5 13.Bc4 Qe4 14.Bd3 Qd5 15.O-O $5 dxe3 ( 15...Bf6 16.Rac1 $36 ) 16.fxe3 Nd8 $140 17.Rad1 Qc6 18.Qe2 $36 [%cal Gf3e5,Ge3e4] ) 7.dxc3 { must be studied in comparison to the leading text: } 7...Qc7 ( 7...Qxd1+ 8.Kxd1 Nc6 ( 8...Be7 9.e4 O-O 10.Kc2 $14 [%cal Gc1f4] ) ( 8...Bd6 9.e4 ) ( 8...b6 9.Bb5+ Bd7 10.a4 Bd6 11.Kc2 Ke7 12.e4 $14 ) 9.e4 b6 10.Bf4 Bb7 11.Kc2 $14 ) 8.Qc2 Be7 9.Bb2 Nc6 10.Be2 ( 10.Bd3 h6 ) 10...b6 ( { perhaps Black should at first take care about his monarch and evacuate it by } 10...Bd7 11.O-O-O O-O-O 12.h4 $1 h6 $140 13.h5 $14 ) 11.O-O-O Bb7 12.h4 h6 13.g4 $14 ) 6.dxc3 $5 ( 6.bxc3 g6 { is just reaching the hot lines of the Gruenfeld. } ) 6...Qc7 { The main continuation. } ( { Black must be on alert in the queenless endgame after } 6...Qxd1+ 7.Kxd1 { and now: } 7...Nc6 ( 7...b6 8.Bb5+ $1 Bd7 9.a4 a6 $6 ( { the trade of the light-squared bishops favours White, so } 9...Nc6 { is preferable, even though White has the better chances after } 10.e4 { as well } ) 10.Bxd7+ Nxd7 11.e4 e6 12.Bf4 f6 13.Nd2 Be7 14.Nc4 Kf7 15.Kc2 e5 { This is already a concession, but Black has serious trouble in meeting the doubling of the rooks along the d-file. It is remarkable how even an elite GM can go down practically without fight because of an innocent mistake in the opening! } 16.Rhd1 Ke6 17.Be3 Rhb8 18.f4 exf4 19.Bxf4 Rb7 20.Rd5 $16 { and White won on move 53, Erdos - Nepomniachtchi, Hersonissos, 2017 } ) ( 7...Bf5 8.Nd2 $1 [%cal Ge3e4] { A concrete and strong move - besides planting the knight on the perfect c4-square, an essential part of White's set-up is to push the e-pawn, which is now inevitably coming next. } 8...Nc6 9.e4 Bg6 ( 9...Bd7 10.Kc2 O-O-O 11.a4 $14 ) 10.Bb5 Rc8 ( { strategically risky, to say the least, is } 10...O-O-O $6 11.Bxc6 bxc6 12.f3 $14 ) 11.h4 h5 12.f3 a6 13.Be2 ( { here } 13.Bxc6+ $6 Rxc6 14.Nc4 { is an utterly different story, Black's queenside is compact and he must feel confident by playing } 14...f6 ) 13...e6 14.a4 Rd8 15.Ke1 Na5 16.Nc4 Nb3 17.Rb1 Nxc1 18.Rxc1 $14 ) ( 7...Bg4 8.e4 Nc6 9.Be3 O-O-O+ 10.Kc2 Bxf3 ( 10...e6 11.Nd2 ) 11.gxf3 e6 12.Be2 $14 ) 8.e4 b6 ( 8...Bg4 9.Be3 ) 9.Kc2 Bb7 10.Bf4 ( { compared to the text, } 10.Be3 { looks a bit passive, but White can try } ) ( 10.h4 $5 { at once } ) 10...f6 11.h4 $1 e5 12.Be3 h5 13.Nd2 O-O-O 14.f3 $14 { with better prospects due to the vulnerable d5-square. } ) 7.e4 Nc6 { A logical follow-up compared to: } ( 7...Bg4 8.h3 Bh5 9.Bb5+ Nc6 10.Qa4 $1 Bxf3 11.gxf3 e6 12.Be3 Be7 13.Bxc6+ bxc6 14.O-O-O O-O 15.Rd3 $14 { and the queenside weaknesses may tell in the long run } ) ( 7...e6 { has the drawback of restricting Bc8, while } 8.Bd3 { is bringing its counterpart into play: } 8...Bd7 ( 8...Nc6 9.Qe2 Bd6 10.h4 $1 b6 11.h5 h6 12.Be3 Bb7 13.g3 O-O-O ( { the second player needs courage for playing } 13...O-O { , for he will not be the favourite in the mutual race after } 14.O-O-O ) 14.O-O-O Kb8 15.Bc2 $14 ) 9.h4 ( 9.Qe2 ) 9...Bc6 10.h5 h6 { seems quite similar, White has the additional opportunity } 11.e5 Nd7 $140 12.Bf4 O-O-O 13.Qe2 $14 ) 8.Be3 e6 ( 8...b6 $6 { has a tactical flaw, namely } 9.Qd2 Bb7 10.Bf4 Qc8 ( { the point is that } 10...e5 $6 { fails to } 11.Bxe5 $1 Nxe5 12.Nxe5 $16 ) 11.O-O-O $16 ) 9.Nd2 ( 9.Bd3 $5 Bd6 10.Qe2 ) 9...Be7 { It is hard to recommend anything else than this natural move: } ( 9...Bd6 $6 10.Nc4 Be7 11.Qg4 O-O 12.Bh6 $1 Bf6 13.f4 e5 ( 13...Kh8 14.e5 ) 14.f5 b5 15.Ne3 Ne7 16.h4 Kh8 17.Bg5 $16 ) ( 9...b6 $6 10.Qg4 ( 10.Bb5 $5 Bb7 11.f4 ) 10...Bb7 11.Bf4 ( 11.Nc4 ) 11...e5 12.Be3 $14 ) ( 9...Bd7 10.f4 O-O-O 11.Be2 $14 ) 10.Qg4 ( 10.f4 $5 O-O 11.Qh5 { is possible, but White has usually another route for the queen in mind. } ) 10...O-O 11.Qg3 Bd6 $1 ( { Here too, White would be happy to see the queens off the board - } 11...Qxg3 12.hxg3 b6 13.g4 ( 13.a4 Bb7 14.f3 $14 { Bok - Tiglon, chess.com INT, 2019 } ) ( 13.f4 ) 13...h6 14.O-O-O Rd8 15.Be2 Bb7 16.Rh5 $14 { So - Mamedyarov, chess.com INT, 2019 } ) ( 11...e5 $6 12.Bc4 ) 12.f4 b6 ( { Very similar is } 12...Rd8 13.a4 b6 14.Be2 Bb7 15.O-O $14 { with some spatial advantage. } ) 13.Be2 ( { More restrained and useful than } 13.Bb5 Bb7 14.O-O Rad8 15.e5 Be7 ) ( { Overoptimistic is } 13.h4 Bb7 14.h5 h6 ) 13...Bb7 14.O-O Rad8 ( 14...Rfe8 15.Rae1 Bf8 16.Bb5 Rad8 17.Nf3 $14 ) 15.e5 Be7 16.Rae1 $14 

