 { [%evp 0,62,19,19,26,-2,-2,-12,-24,-67,-11,-7,-10,-24,3,18,44,34,52,1,19,11,33, -15,1,14,22,22,4,20,17,4,4,11,7,-5,12,-14,-15,-7,-13,-44,-16,-16,-14,17,21,44, 8,15,20,-5,19,8,24,24,24,12,19,22,26,6,12,30,22] } 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.g3 d5 4.Bg2 dxc4 { If Black does not want to be tricked by the move order and finds himself in an undesirable Catalan line, then this is the proper moment for taking this pawn. Otherwise, the d2-d4 push is expected to come at any time: } ( { Both } 4...c6 5.d4 { and } ) ( 4...Nbd7 5.d4 { are transposing to the Catalan } ( 5.O-O dxc4 6.Qa4 { is very close to the leading text and may soon transpose to it } ) ) ( 4...a6 5.b3 ( 5.d4 dxc4 { reaches yet another popular line in the Catalan } ) 5...d4 ( 5...Be7 6.Bb2 O-O 7.O-O dxc4 ( 7...b5 8.d4 Bb7 9.cxd5 exd5 10.Nbd2 $14 ) ( 7...b6 { can also be met by } 8.d4 Bb7 9.cxd5 exd5 10.Ne5 Nbd7 11.Nd2 Re8 12.Rc1 $14 ) 8.bxc4 c5 9.a4 ( 9.Ne5 Ra7 ) 9...b6 10.a5 $14 ) 6.e3 c5 7.O-O Nc6 { has directed the game to a position of Benoni type. Here White has the curious } 8.Qe2 $5 Bd6 ( { in case of } 8...Be7 9.exd4 cxd4 10.Ne5 Nxe5 11.Qxe5 O-O 12.Ba3 $14 { may demonstrate that a7-a6 is useless } ) 9.exd4 cxd4 10.Bb2 O-O 11.Nxd4 Nxd4 12.Bxd4 Bxg3 { and he can add more fuel into the fire by means of } 13.Bxf6 Qxf6 14.hxg3 Qxa1 15.Nc3 Qb2 16.Rb1 Qa3 17.b4 a5 { The next step of this pawn liberates the stranded queen, but White is able to exert serious queenside pressure after } 18.b5 Qc5 19.Qd3 $1 [%cal Gc3e4] f5 20.b6 $44 [%cal Gb1b5] ) ( 4...Bd6 5.O-O O-O 6.d4 { is another version of the Catalan, in which White has kept his dark squared bishop at place by avoiding its counterpart's check from b4: } 6...c6 ( 6...b6 7.Nc3 ( 7.Ne5 $5 Bb7 8.Bg5 ) 7...Bb7 8.cxd5 ( 8.Ne5 Nbd7 9.Bf4 Ne4 10.Rc1 $14 ) 8...exd5 9.Nb5 Be7 10.Bf4 Na6 11.Nc3 c6 12.Qc2 $14 ) 7.Qc2 ( 7.Nc3 Nbd7 8.Nd2 ) 7...Nbd7 8.Nbd2 [%cal Ge2e4] { Here is the first difference - had Bc1 already been lured to this square, White would have had yet to prepare the central advance. } 8...Re8 ( 8...b6 $6 9.e4 dxe4 10.Nxe4 Nxe4 11.Qxe4 Bb7 12.Rd1 Qc7 13.Qc2 c5 14.dxc5 Bxc5 15.Bf4 $16 ) ( { the second one is revealed after } 8...e5 9.cxd5 cxd5 10.dxe5 Nxe5 11.Nxe5 Bxe5 12.Nf3 Bd6 13.b3 $14 { and Bc1 will occupy its usual working diagonal } ) 9.Rd1 Qe7 ( { the line } 9...e5 10.cxd5 cxd5 11.dxe5 Nxe5 12.Nxe5 Bxe5 13.Nf3 $14 { does not differ from the relevant one on the previous move } ) 10.Re1 $1 ( { it is never easy to take a move back, but this X-ray is going to tell soon; the immediate } 10.e4 { is neutralized by } 10...dxe4 11.Nxe4 Nxe4 12.Qxe4 e5 13.Re1 Qf8 ) 10...e5 ( 10...Qf8 11.b3 e5 12.cxd5 cxd5 13.dxe5 Nxe5 14.Bb2 $14 ) 11.cxd5 cxd5 ( 11...Nxd5 $6 12.e4 Nb4 13.Qb1 $16 ) ( 11...e4 $5 { is interesting, though probably insufficient, as shown by } 12.dxc6 bxc6 13.Ng5 e3 14.Nde4 h6 15.Nxd6 exf2+ 16.Kxf2 Qxd6 17.Nf3 c5 18.Bf4 Qe7 19.Nd2 $5 Ng4+ 20.Kg1 Ne3 21.Bxe3 Qxe3+ 22.Kh1 Rb8 { and White can return the pawn and take over the initiative by means of } 23.Nc4 $1 Qxd4 24.Rad1 $14 ) 12.e4 ( { besides, White can prevent any complications on the board by } 12.dxe5 Nxe5 13.Nxe5 Qxe5 14.Nf3 { and rely on play against the isolated d5-pawn - } 14...Qe4 15.Qb3 Qb4 $14 ) 12...dxe4 13.Nxe4 Nxe4 14.Qxe4 Nf6 15.Qh4 e4 16.Bg5 Bb4 ( 16...h6 $6 17.Bxf6 Qxf6 18.Rxe4 $16 ) 17.Re2 $1 ( 17.Bxf6 gxf6 18.Re2 f5 $13 ) ( 17.Re3 Qf8 18.Ne5 Bd2 $13 ) 17...Bg4 ( 17...Bf5 $5 18.a3 $140 Qd6 { is a plausible alternative, after } 19.Bxf6 exf3 20.Rxe8+ Rxe8 21.Bxf3 gxf6 22.axb4 Qxb4 { White, indeed, has a draw in his pocket, while } 23.Qxf6 Bh3 24.Qg5+ Kh8 25.Qc1 Qxd4 26.Bxb7 Re2 27.Qc3 Rd2 $14 { is very likely to result in an ending with an extra pawn for him, though left only on the kingside } ) 18.Re3 Bf5 ( 18...Bxf3 19.Bxf3 ) 19.Bxf6 Qxf6 20.Qxf6 gxf6 21.Nh4 Bg6 22.Nxg6 hxg6 23.Bxe4 $14 ) 5.Qa4+ ( { White might have trouble in regaining the pawn after } 5.O-O a6 ) 5...Nbd7 { The most natural reply, here is also a review of the alternatives: } ( 5...Q