1 Qe7 16.Na4 $1 Bxd4 ( 16...Ba3 $2 { did not solve Black's problems after } 17.Bxa3 Qxa3 18.f4 Nc6 19.Nb5 $16 [%cal Ge4e5] { D. Anton Guijarro - Kir. Georgiev, Batumi, 2019 } ) 17.Rxd4 Nc6 18.Rd2 Rfd8 19.Rad1 $14 { /+/- } ) 14.Re2 $1 Ne5 ( 14...Qb8 15.Rd2 a6 16.Qe2 $14 { Grischuk - Aronian, London, 2015 } ) 15.Na4 $1 ( { much stronger than } 15.Rd2 Qe7 ) 15...Bxd4 16.Bxd4 Nc6 17.Bb2 Qe7 18.Qe1 Rfd8 19.Rd1 { with continuous pressure, Artemiev - Matlakov, Warsaw, 2021 } ) 10.dxc5 Bxc5 11.Nbd2 ( { As usual, it is preferable to avoid even single exchanges like } 11.Nc3 Nxc3 12.Bxc3 Nd7 { in order not to release the tension } ) 11...Qe7 { looks solid, Black has every chance to gradually equalize: } ( 11...Nd7 12.Ne4 $5 ( 12.a3 a5 ) ( 12.Rc1 Qe7 ) 12...Be7 13.Qd4 N7f6 ( 13...N5f6 14.Ne5 Nxe5 15.Qxe5 $14 ) 14.Ne5 $1 $36 ( 14.Rac1 { allows } 14...Nb4 ) 14...Nxe4 ( 14...Rc8 15.Rac1 ) 15.Qxe4 Bf6 16.Rac1 Rc8 17.Rxc8 Qxc8 18.Rc1 Qa8 19.Bf3 $5 Rc8 ( 19...h6 20.h4 $14 ) ( 19...Nc3 $6 { does not achieve anything, for after } 20.Qf4 $1 { the tactics are working for White } ) 20.Rxc8+ Qxc8 21.Qc4 $1 h6 ( 21...Qd8 22.h4 $14 ) 22.h4 $14 ) 12.a3 ( 12.Qb1 $5 [%cal Gd2e4] Rd8 ( 12...Nd7 $144 13.a3 a5 14.Ne4 Rac8 ) 13.Ne4 Nd7 $11 ) 12...a5 13.b4 $5 ( 13.Ne5 Nf6 14.e3 Rd8 15.Qe2 Bxg2 16.Kxg2 Qb7+ 17.Qf3 Qxf3+ 18.Nexf3 Nbd7 19.Rfc1 $14 ) 13...axb4 14.axb4 Bxb4 15.Rxa8 Bxa8 16.Qa1 Nd7 17.Bxg7 Rc8 { and White could not make use of the missing g-pawn in front of the enemy king - } 18.Bh6 ( 18.Qa6 Bb7 $1 19.Qxb7 Rc7 20.Qa8+ Kxg7 $11 ) 18...Nc3 19.Nd4 ( { calmer is } 19.Qa6 Qd8 { with approximate equality; after the text move White's minor pieces are slightly hanging } ) 19...Bxg2 20.Kxg2 Qf6 21.Qa6 Rd8 22.Be3 Nd5 23.Nc6 Nb8 $1 24.Nxb8 Rxb8 25.Nf3 Nxe3+ 26.fxe3 Bc5 { and Black had little to worry about in Anton Guijarro - Salgado Lopez, Linares, 2020. } ) 7.cxd5 Nxd5 ( { The other way to capture } 7...exd5 8.d4 Nc6 { and } ( 8...Ne4 9.Bb2 ) 9.Bb2 { leads us back to Chapter 9 and one of the main lines of the Tarrasch - } 9...Ne4 10.dxc5 ( 10.Nc3 Bf6 ) 10...Bxc5 11.Nc3 Nxc3 12.Bxc3 d4 ( 12...Bf5 13.e3 Be4 14.Ne5 $14 ) 13.Bb2 Bf5 ( 13...Bg4 14.h3 ) 14.b4 Nxb4 ( 14...Bxb4 15.Nxd4 Nxd4 16.Qxd4 Qxd4 17.Bxd4 $14 ) 15.Bxd4 $14 ) 8.Bb2 Nc6 ( 8...b6 9.d4 Bb7 { -6...b6 } ) 9.d4 { White cannot postpone this central strike forever. } ( { For instance, Black can react to } 9.Nc3 { with } 9...Bf6 ) 9...cxd4 10.Nxd4 Bd7 ( { An essential branch is } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 Bf6 12.Qd2 { , when Black's shot at equality is the clever tactics } 12...Nf4 $1 ( 12...Bxb2 $6 13.Qxb2 $14 ) 13.gxf4 Qxd2 14.Nxd2 Bxb2 15.Rad1 Bf6 ( 15...Rb8 16.Nc4 { may just transpose } ) 16.Nc4 Rb8 17.Ne5 ( 17.b4 b5 18.Na5 Rb6 ) 17...Rd8 18.Rxd8+ Bxd8 19.Rd1 Be7 ( { or } 19...Bc7 20.e3 Kf8 21.Nd7+ Bxd7 22.Rxd7 { , when White can win the b7-pawn only by exchanging the rooks, e.g. } 22...Bb6 23.Kf1 Ke8 24.Rxb7 Rxb7 25.Bxb7 Bc5 $11 ) 20.Nd7 Bxd7 21.Rxd7 Kf8 22.Bxb7 Rd8 23.Rc7 a5 $14 { with decent chances to hold due to the opposite-coloured bishops, Ding Liren - Nepomniachtchi, Astana, 2023. } ) 11.Na3 $5 { Leaving the big diagonal open for Bb2. } ( { The exchange } 11.Nc3 Nxc3 12.Bxc3 { is enabling Black's task, as shown by } 12...Rc8 13.Rc1 $140 Ba3 14.Rc2 Qe7 15.Nxc6 Bxc6 16.Qd4 f5 $11 ) 11...Nxd4 ( { Very similar is the picture after } 11...Bf6 12.Qd2 $5 ( 12.Nc4 Nxd4 13.Bxd4 Bb5 ) 12...Nxd4 ( 12...Qe7 13.Nc4 $14 ) 13.Bxd4 Bc6 14.Rfd1 { , when the practice has seen: } 14...Bxd4 ( 14...Ne7 $6 { has left Black suffering for the draw - } 15.Bxf6 Qxd2 16.Rxd2 gxf6 17.Bxc6 ( 17.Rad1 $14 ) 17...Nxc6 18.Rd7 Rab8 19.Nc4 $14 { Artemiev - Nakamura, chess24.com INT, 2020 } ) 15.Qxd4 Qe7 16.Nc4 Rfd8 ( 16...Nb4 $6 17.Qd6 Qxd6 18.Nxd6 Bxg2 19.Kxg2 $14 { Giri - Leko, chess24.com INT, 2020 } ) 17.Ne5 Be8 18.Qb2 $14 ) 12.Qxd4 Bf6 13.Qd2 Bc6 14.Nc4 Ne7 { Without Rf1-d1 this retreat is more justified. } ( 14...Bxb2 15.Qxb2 $14 ) 15.Qxd8 ( { Now } 15.Rfd1 { will just lead to mass simplifications and equality after } 15...Qx