 { [%evp 0,66,20,20,22,6,24,12,3,-36,-28,-32,-33,-31,-27,-6,-3,-6,10,-10,-10,3, -7,0,-8,-14,-24,-41,-29,-14,-6,-2,-10,6,3,10,12,0,6,-12,-8,3,9,16,47,38,64,10, 91,-9,48,21,57,54,61,67,0,0,0,0,21,39,0,0,0,0,0,0,0] } 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 c6 3.g3 d5 4.Bg2 dxc4 { The most principled reply compared to: } ( 4...g6 5.b3 Bg7 6.Bb2 O-O 7.O-O b6 ( 7...a5 8.d3 a4 9.Nbd2 $14 ) ( 7...Bg4 8.d4 $14 ) 8.d4 Bb7 9.Nc3 Nbd7 ( 9...e6 10.e3 { The position is almost symmetrical, the the small difference along the c-file is nevertheless in White's favour and his chances are preferable after } 10...Qe7 11.Ne5 Na6 12.Qe2 $14 { ; similar is the situation after the textmove } ) 10.e3 ( 10.Ne5 e6 11.e3 ) ( 10.Qc2 ) 10...e6 11.Ne5 $1 Nxe5 ( 11...Qe7 12.f4 $14 [%cal Gd1e2,Ga1d1] ) ( 11...Qc7 12.f4 ) 12.dxe5 Nd7 13.f4 f6 14.cxd5 cxd5 15.exf6 ( 15.Nxd5 fxe5 16.Nf6+ Qxf6 17.Bxb7 Rad8 18.Qe2 Qe7 $11 ) ( 15.Bh3 $5 ) 15...Bxf6 ( 15...Nxf6 16.Qe2 $14 ) 16.Rc1 Rc8 17.Rf2 Qe7 18.Rfc2 $14 ) ( 4...Bf5 { is an invitation for } 5.Qb3 { and now: } 5...Qb6 { is the most reasonable reply, so is with } ( 5...Qc7 6.cxd5 $1 cxd5 7.Nc3 e6 8.d3 Nc6 9.Bf4 Qb6 ( { preserving the queens by } 9...Qd7 { will cause more headaches after } 10.O-O Be7 11.Ne5 Nxe5 12.Bxe5 O-O 13.e4 $16 ) 10.Qxb6 axb6 11.Nb5 $5 ( { a different plan is } 11.Nh4 Bg6 12.Nxg6 hxg6 13.O-O $14 { , but it is more typical to leave Bf5 restricted the d3-pawn and harass it later with the kingside ones } ) 11...Kd7 12.Ne5+ Nxe5 13.Bxe5 Bb4+ 14.Bc3 Bxc3+ 15.Nxc3 Rhc8 16.Kd2 $14 [%cal Gf2f4] ) ( 5...Qc8 6.d3 e6 7.Nh4 Bg4 8.h3 Bh5 9.g4 Bg6 10.O-O $14 ) 6.d3 { and now: } 6...e6 ( 6...dxc4 $6 7.Qxc4 Nbd7 8.O-O e5 9.Nbd2 Be7 ( 9...Bd6 10.Qc2 ) 10.b3 O-O 11.Bb2 $16 ) ( 6...Nbd7 7.Qxb6 axb6 ( 7...Nxb6 { seems to be the lesser evil - } 8.cxd5 cxd5 9.Nc3 $14 ) 8.Nd4 $1 Bg6 9.cxd5 Nxd5 ( 9...cxd5 10.Nb5 Rc8 11.N1c3 e6 12.Bf4 $16 ) 10.Bxd5 cxd5 11.Nb5 Rc8 12.N1c3 e6 13.Be3 $16 ) 7.Be3 Qxb3 ( 7...dxc4 $6 8.Qxc4 Qxb2 9.O-O $16 ) 8.axb3 a6 9.Nh4 Bg6 10.Bd2 $5 ( 10.Nc3 Bb4 ) 10...Nbd7 11.b4 Bd6 12.Nxg6 hxg6 13.O-O $14 ) ( 4...Bg4 5.Ne5 { and it is not easy to point out the safest retreat of Bg4: } 5...Be6 ( 5...Bf5 6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Nc3 { is even more unpleasant with the other knight already on e5: } 7...Nbd7 ( 7...e6 $6 { seems ill-timed in the view of the vigorous } 8.g4 $1 Be4 ( { or } 8...Bg6 9.h4 { at once } ) 9.f3 Bg6 10.h4 Bd6 11.d4 h6 12.Nxg6 fxg6 13.Qd3 Kf7 14.Bd2 $16 ) 8.Qa4 $1 ( { this sally is the challenge compared to } 8.d4 e6 { and Black can take a deep breath } ) 8...e6 9.g4 $1 Bc2 ( 9...Bg6 10.h4 ) 10.Qxc2 $1 ( { better than the greedy } 10.Nxf7 Bxa4 11.Nxd8 Rxd8 12.Nxa4 Nxg4 13.Bh3 h5 14.f3 Nge5 15.Bxe6 d4 $44 { and White should spend more time on saving Na4 } ) 10...Nxe5 11.g5 Nfd7 12.d4 Nc6 13.e4 Nxd4 14.Qd3 Bc5 15.exd5 { and Bg2 is a big asset - } 15...O-O 16.O-O $14 ) ( 5...Bh5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 ( 6...cxd5 $6 { looks more than risky because of } 7.Qa4+ Nbd7 8.Nc3 e6 9.g4 Bg6 10.h4 $16 ) 7.Qb3 Qb6 ( { Black is able to protect the attacked b7-pawn without sacrificing another one, but his opponent's central preponderance is indisputable after both } 7...Qc7 8.d4 ) ( { and } 7...Nd7 8.Bxd5 Nxe5 9.Bg2 $14 ) 8.Bxd5 cxd5 9.Qxd5 e6 10.Qe4 $14 ) 6.cxd5 Bxd5 { may well be Black's best - } 7.Nf3 [%cal Gb1c3] e5 ( { possible is } 7...c5 8.Nc3 Bc6 9.O-O e6 10.Qc2 $14 [%cal Gf1d1,Gd2d4,Ge2e4] ) 8.Nc3 e4 ( 8...Bxf3 9.Bxf3 $14 ) 9.Ne5 $14 ) 5.O-O Nbd7 { Black's most popular continuation and deservedly so: } ( { It is known for long that } 5...b5 $6 { is running into } 6.d3 $1 cxd3 7.Ne5 $1 { and, with so many files and diagonals open, White is enjoying a great compensation, e.g. } 7...Bb7 ( 7...Qc7 8.Nxd3 e5 { cannot entirely suppress the opponent's initiative - } 9.Bg5 Be7 10.Qc1 Be6 11.Nc3 a6 12.a4 $16 ) 8.a4 $5 ( 8.Nxd3 ) 8...b4 9.a5 Qc8 10.Nxd3 e6 11.Qa4 $14 ) ( 5...Bf5 6.Na3 e5 ( 6...b5 $6 7.b3 cxb3 8.Qxb3 e6 9.d3 $16 ) 7.Nxc4 e4 8.Nfe5 Nbd7 9.d4 $14 ) ( 5...g6 6.Na3 b5 ( 6...Qd5 $6 7.Qc2 Be6 8.Qc3 $1 $16 [%cal Gf3d4] ) 7.Ne5 a6 ( 7...Q