oves of the other bishop are coming in confirmation of the annotation to 7.Rd1!? - } 7...Be6 8.b3 cxb3 9.axb3 Bd5 ( 9...g6 10.e4 Bg7 11.d4 $44 [%cal Gh2h3,Gb1c3, Gc1e3] ) 10.Nc3 Bxf3 11.Bxf3 e6 12.d4 Bb4 13.e4 O-O 14.Ne2 Qe7 15.Nf4 a5 16.Nd3 $44 ) ( { and } 7...Bg4 8.Na3 Qd5 9.b3 cxb3 10.axb3 e6 11.Nc4 Qd8 12.Na5 $44 ) ( { , while locking it by } 7...e6 { is not logical - } 8.a4 a5 9.Na3 $14 ) 8.Nc3 Bg7 { The consistent move, it is a bit late to think about the other bishop: } ( 8...Bg4 $6 9.a4 $1 a5 10.Ne5 Be6 11.d4 cxd3 12.Nxd3 $14 ) ( 8...Bf5 9.e4 Bg4 10.d3 cxd3 11.Rxd3 $44 [%cal Gf3e5,Ga2a4] ) ( 8...Nfd5 $5 { , from the other side, deserves serious attention, for example } 9.d3 $5 ( { Black is fine after } 9.Nxd5 cxd5 10.Qc3 f6 $13 ) 9...Nb4 ( 9...cxd3 10.Rxd3 Bd7 11.Ne5 Bg7 12.Nxd7 Qxd7 13.Qb3 Qe6 14.Nxd5 Nxd5 15.Qxb7 O-O 16.Rd2 Rfb8 17.Qa6 $14 ) 10.Qb1 cxd3 11.a3 N4d5 12.Rxd3 Bd7 $1 13.Ne5 Be6 14.Bf4 Qc8 15.Bxd5 { and now: } 15...Bxd5 $1 ( 15...Nxd5 16.Nxd5 cxd5 ( { but not } 16...Bxd5 $2 17.Rxd5 $1 cxd5 18.Qd3 $16 { and Ke8 is in trouble } ) 17.Qd1 Bg7 18.Rc1 Qd8 19.Qa4+ Kf8 20.Nf3 $44 ) 16.Nxd5 cxd5 17.a4 Bg7 18.a5 Nc4 19.Rxd5 Qe6 20.Qd3 Bxe5 21.Qxc4 Bxf4 22.Qa4+ Kf8 23.Qd4 f6 24.gxf4 Qxe2 25.Rd7 Qg4+ $11 ) 9.d3 cxd3 10.Rxd3 Bd7 11.e4 ( { In case of } 11.Ne5 { Black is by no means obliged to go for the line from above (see 9... cxd3) with 11...Nfd5, he has } 11...Qc8 12.Nxd7 $140 Nfxd7 $11 { at his disposal. } ) 11...Qc8 12.a4 $1 ( { It is hard to believe, but natural developing moves like } 12.Bf4 $6 O-O 13.Rad1 Bg4 $15 { in Ronat - Hervet, ICCF email, 2011, do not cause Black any harm. } ) 12...Bg4 $1 ( 12...a5 $6 { is risky because of } 13.Be3 Nc4 14.Bd4 $16 ) ( { So is with } 12...Be6 $6 13.Ng5 Bc4 14.Rd1 h6 15.Nf3 $14 ) 13.a5 ( 13.Ne5 Be6 ) 13...Nbd7 14.Rd1 ( 14.h3 Bxf3 15.Rxf3 O-O $13 ) 14...O-O { Black has no particular reason to delay this. } ( 14...Nc5 $143 15.Be3 Na6 16.Qb3 O-O 17.Rac1 $44 ) 15.h3 Bxf3 16.Bxf3 Rd8 17.Be3 $44 b5 $1 { A well-timed co